Exercises solved
Q1. A 48V supply is connected to a 1.2kΩ resistor.
(a) Calculate the current in mA
(b) Calculate the power dissipated
(c) Calculate the energy consumed in 2 hours
(d) The resistor is rated 2W. Is it operating safely with a 2× derating margin?
Q2. You measure 65mA flowing through an unknown component when 15.6V is applied across it.
(a) Calculate the resistance
(b) Calculate the power
(c) Choose a resistor from the E24 series (values: 10, 12, 15, 18, 22, 27, 33, 39, 47, 56, 68, 82 and their decade multiples). Which standard value is closest?
(d) What is the percentage error introduced by using the standard value?
(e) What minimum power rating should you specify?
Q3. A MOSFET in a solar inverter carries 25A continuously. R_DS(on) = 0.012Ω at 25°C. The datasheet shows R_DS(on) doubles at 175°C junction temperature.
(a) Conduction loss at 25°C
(b) Conduction loss at 175°C
(c) A better MOSFET has R_DS(on) = 0.004Ω at 175°C. Calculate the power saving.
(d) Over a year of 10 hours/day operation, how many kWh does the better MOSFET save?
(e) At ₦200 per kWh, what is the annual energy cost saving?
Q4. A PCB trace for a 3A current path: copper (ρ = 1.68×10⁻⁸ Ω·m), 60mm long, 35µm thick (1oz copper).
(a) If the trace is 0.5mm wide, calculate resistance and power loss at 3A
(b) If the trace is 2mm wide, calculate resistance and power loss at 3A
(c) What width would give power loss below 50mW at 3A?
(d) At 80°C operating temperature, what is the resistance of the 2mm trace? (α = 0.00393/°C, T₀ = 25°C)
Q5. Three resistors are connected to a 24V supply. R1 = 100Ω, R2 = 150Ω, R3 = 200Ω — all in separate branches each directly across the 24V supply (parallel arrangement). For each resistor find:
(a) Current through it
(b) Power dissipated
(c) Total current from supply
(d) Total power. Verify: P_total = V × I_total
Q6. Derivation question — no numbers, pure algebra.
(a) Starting from P = V×I and V = IR, derive P = I²R showing every step
(b) Starting from P = V×I and I = V/R, derive P = V²/R showing every step
(c) A component dissipates 50W at 10A. What is its resistance?
(d) The same component now carries 15A. What is its power dissipation?
(e) A component dissipates 50W with 20V across it. What current flows and what is the resistance?
Q7. Resistivity and wire design.
A motor winding uses 200m of copper wire, circular cross-section, diameter = 0.8mm. ρ = 1.68×10⁻⁸ Ω·m, α = 0.00393/°C.
(a) Cross-sectional area A = π(d/2)²
(b) DC resistance at 25°C
(c) Motor runs at 120°C. Resistance at 120°C.
(d) Winding current = 4A. Copper loss at 120°C.
(e) If the wire diameter is increased to 1.0mm, find the new resistance at 120°C and new copper loss. What is the percentage improvement?
